{"accepted":[{"assertion":"Erdős Problem #948: declared status 'open'. Formalized: no. Is there a function $f(n)$ and a $k$ such that in any $k$-colouring of the integers there exists a sequence $a_1<\\cdots$ such that $a_n<f(n)$ for infinitely many $n$ and the set\\[\\left\\{ \\sum_{i\\in S}a_i : \\textrm{finite }S\\right\\}\\]does not contain all colours? Current best: Erd\\H{o}s initially asked whether this is possible with the set being monochromatic, but Galvin showed that this is not always possible, considering the two colouring where, writing $n=2^km$ with $m$ odd, we colour $n$ red if $m\\geq F(k)$ and blue if $m<F(k)$ (for some sufficiently quickly growing $F$). Prize: no. Tags: number theory, ramsey theory.","id":"vf_63df4acd5091690e","trust":"signed","type":"theoretical"},{"assertion":"AI-contributions wiki claim — wiki: Full solution (Lean).","id":"vf_77ed0338df3e7508","trust":"signed","type":"theoretical"},{"assertion":"Formal-Conjectures statement: FC 948 (PR #3588) [in-pr] https://github.com/google-deepmind/formal-conjectures/pull/3588.","id":"vf_fa3b4429a2eec6ec","trust":"signed","type":"theoretical"}],"accepted_activity":false,"activity":[],"activity_types":[],"attempt_count":0,"banked_attempt_count":0,"commits":[],"dependency_impact":"none","detail_url":"problems/948.json","draft_proposals":[],"edges":[{"evidence":"Problem identity derived from the accepted finding's pinned source anchor.","inferred":true,"relation":"describes","source":"vf_63df4acd5091690e","source_root":"sha256:d3db36661e28b7570fc8704bf8455b80d8382beded47d069f2c386144d90a238","target":"erdos:948","trust":"signed"},{"evidence":"Problem identity derived from the accepted finding's pinned source anchor.","inferred":true,"relation":"describes","source":"vf_77ed0338df3e7508","source_root":"sha256:d3db36661e28b7570fc8704bf8455b80d8382beded47d069f2c386144d90a238","target":"erdos:948","trust":"signed"},{"evidence":"Problem identity derived from the accepted finding's pinned source ancho